The atoms or molecules that make up a solid are attracting each other with strong attractions, and because atoms or molecules are regularly arranged, they cannot move freely, so they are only vibrating in place. Continuous lowering of the temperature is expected to stop the vibration of these solid molecules, which is about -273Â°C, and this temperature is called absolute zero (0 K). On the contrary, if the temperature of the solid is increased, the vibration of molecules or atoms is accelerated and the regular molecular arrangement of the solid collapses and turns into a liquid when it reaches the melting point.

As a way of describing the motion of solid molecules, the set of atoms or molecules that make up a solid can be likened to a set of heavy particles connected by very light springs with little mass, and intermolecular bonds can be thought of as each spring binds adjacent particles. When an external force is applied, the entire set of particles is compressed, expanded, or distorted, just like the properties of solids we know.

"In the case of heating a solid, if the heated molecule vibrates more, the neighboring molecules vibrate together, explaining the conduction of heat. If the solid particles become too large to break the spring, the regular arrangement collapses and melts into a liquid."
